{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015np8qpvP4GfQaiqviAKFSd","type":"tool_result","content":"207:- [ ] Production requests without a valid `cf-access-jwt-assertion` are denied before rendering any page.\n208:- [ ] Production requests with a valid JWT but missing/invalid email claim are denied.\n209:- [ ] JWT validation uses `jose` (`createRemoteJWKSet` + `jwtVerify`) with configured Cloudflare issuer and audience; custom crypto/JWKS verification code is removed.\n210:- [ ] The normalized Cloudflare email is attached to server-side request context and never accepted from an untrusted browser header.\n211:- [ ] `peek` does not maintain a second global env allowlist for base access; base access remains Cloudflare policy.\n212:- [ ] Development bypass is explicit and local-only, for example `PEEK_DEV_ACCESS_EMAIL=dev@example.com`; production never uses this bypass.\n213:- [ ] Unit tests cover missing token, invalid token, missing email, case normalization, trusted context propagation, and development bypass behavior.\n220:- [ ] Access checks are centralized in one server-only module, not repeated in pages.\n221:- [ ] Local role policy is defined in a checked-in server-only module such as `peek/src/server/access-policy.ts`, or in a local config file loaded only by server code.\n222:- [ ] Role membership supports exact emails such as `alice@example.com`.\n223:- [ ] Role membership supports wildcard domains such as `*@example.com`.\n224:- [ ] Role matching is case-insensitive and trims whitespace.\n225:- [ ] Initial roles are limited to `business` and `admin`.\n226:- [ ] A verified email resolves to one effective role; `admin` is the superset role and wins if exact-email and wildcard-domain entries both match.\n227:- [ ] Route prefixes can require `business`, `admin`, or both; sensitive routes such as `/audit` require `admin`.\n228:- [ ] Mutation action ids can require one or more roles, for example `kol_rate.update` requiring `business` or `admin`.\n229:- [ ] Unknown route prefixes use the documented default access behavior; unknown mutation action ids deny.\n230:- [ ] Unit tests cover exact email, wildcard domain, admin precedence, route allow/deny, action allow/deny, case normalization, and invalid policy entries.\n237:- [ ] `peek` has a persistent app shell with navigation groups: Users, Growth, Games, Economy, Operations, Audit, Access.\n238:- [ ] The shell shows the currently verified actor email and resolved local role.\n239:- [ ] The shell never shows pages that the actor cannot access.\n240:- [ ] The first screen remains operationally dense: global search, attention items, a small metric strip, and direct access to the user/referral table.\n241:- [ ] The shell includes no marketing-style hero, decorative analytics filler, or non-actionable dashboard cards.\n242:- [ ] Empty states explain the absence of data in operator terms, for example \"No failed claims in this time window.\"\n249:- [ ] Each metric has a stable id, label, value, source table/query, time window, and \"as of\" timestamp.\n250:- [ ] Each metric has a short definition available in the UI or adjacent help text.\n251:- [ ] Each summary metric links to the filtered detail rows behind it when detail rows exist.\n252:- [ ] Each page states whether data is live, cached, manually refreshed, or sampled.\n253:- [ ] Sparse data renders explicit empty states instead of zeros that can be mistaken for measured outcomes.\n254:- [ ] Monetary values are displayed with units and retain lamports as the precise underlying value.\n255:- [ ] Points and counts use integer formatting; no float rounding for ledger values.\n256:- [ ] Filters are visible and URL-addressable so an admin can share a specific investigation state internally.\n257:- [ ] Default filters prevent accidental unbounded queries on high-volume pages.\n264:- [ ] Search accepts `user_id`, username, wallet, referral code, Telegram username, Telegram provider account id, round PDA, match id, and tx signature.\n265:- [ ] Search results are grouped by entity type: user, referral, linked account, round, transaction, queue event.\n266:- [ ] Each result includes enough context to disambiguate similar matches.\n267:- [ ] Search queries are server-side and bounded.\n268:- [ ] Search does not require backend route changes.\n269:- [ ] Searching for sensitive identifiers logs a `peek.search` operator event with actor email, query class, result counts, and no access tokens or secrets.\n276:- [ ] User detail shows profile identity from `player_profiles`: user id, username, wallet, created date, avatar URL if present, heat multiplier, and profile points slot.\n277:- [ ] User detail shows linked account state from `linked_accounts`, including Telegram metadata when present.\n278:- [ ] User detail shows latest Telegram link token records from `telegram_link_tokens` for support/audit context.\n279:- [ ] User detail shows referral code, inbound referrer, outbound referees, KOL rate if present, earnings, rebates, and claim states.\n280:- [ ] User detail shows points balance, lifetime points, recent point grants, recent crate drops, and challenge assignment summary.\n281:- [ ] User detail shows recent game entries and transactions across FlipYou, Pot Shot, and Close Call.\n282:- [ ] User detail flags obvious attention states: failed claim, dead queue event for the user, active fraud flag, pending SOL crate payout, or suspicious referral self/loop inconsistency.\n283:- [ ] User detail uses tabs or anchored sections so the page stays scannable.\n290:- [ ] Referral overview shows total referrers, referred users, activated referred users, referral earnings, referee rebates, pending claims, failed claims, and KOL count.\n291:- [ ] Top referrers table includes referral code, user id, username, wallet, referee count, active referee count, referred wager volume, referrer earnings, and pending claim amount.\n292:- [ ] KOL table reads from `referral_kol_rates` and shows rate, wallet, set_by, created_at, updated_at, and linked performance metrics.\n293:- [ ] Claim table reads from `referral_claims` and filters by status, user, amount, requested date, processed date, tx signature, and error.\n294:- [ ] Referral graph/detail allows navigation from referrer to referees and back to user detail.\n295:- [ ] CSV export for filtered referral/KOL tables is allowed only after FR-11 audit logging is implemented.\n302:- [ ] Games overview shows activity by game from `game_entries`: entries, unique users, wagered lamports, settled entries, refunds, payouts, and win/loss counts.\n303:- [ ] FlipYou and Pot Shot round visibility reads from `rounds` and shows phase, pda, match id, creator, target slot, settle attempts, settle tx, result side, winner, created/updated/settled timestamps.\n304:- [ ] Close Call round visibility reads from `closecall_rounds` and shows phase, pda, open/close price fields, outcome, pools, total fee, settle tx, created/settled timestamps.\n305:- [ ] Round detail joins entries from `game_entries` and transactions from `transactions`.\n306:- [ ] Stuck-state filters exist for rounds in nonterminal phases beyond an age threshold, high settle attempts, settled entries without expected transactions, and refunds.\n307:- [ ] Deferred/planned games appear only as documented placeholders until they have persisted data sources.\n314:- [ ] Reward config page reads `reward_config` and displays key, value, updated_at, definition, and expected value type.\n315:- [ ] Reward pool page reads `reward_pool` and `reward_pool_fundings` and displays balance, lifetime funded, lifetime paid, recent fundings, and funding source round ids.\n316:- [ ] Points page reads `player_points` and `point_grants` and supports filtering by user, source type, source id, and date.\n317:- [ ] Crate page reads `crate_drops` and supports filters for crate type, status, trigger type, user, and date.\n318:- [ ] Challenge page reads `campaigns`, `challenges`, `challenge_assignments`, `progress_events`, `completion_bonuses`, and `bonus_completions`.\n319:- [ ] Dogpile page reads `dogpile_events` and related campaign/game activity, showing scheduled, active, ended, and cancelled states.\n320:- [ ] Fraud review page or user-detail section reads `fraud_flags` and exposes open/reviewed/dismissed status as read-only.\n321:- [ ] Challenge definition editing is out of scope.\n322:- [ ] Reward config editing is allowed only for selected keys through the scoped mutation rules in FR-14.\n329:- [ ] Queue overview reads `event_queue` and shows counts by status, event type, attempts, age bucket, and max attempts.\n330:- [ ] Queue table filters by status, event type, id, payload user id when present, scheduled_at, created_at, and age.\n331:- [ ] Queue detail shows payload JSON, error, attempt counts, timestamps, and linked user/round/claim routes when identifiers are present.\n332:- [ ] Dead and failed events are surfaced as attention items on the command center.\n333:- [ ] The page is read-only; retry, cancel, or replay actions require a separate mutation spec.\n334:- [ ] Payload rendering redacts known secrets if any ever appear.\n341:- [ ] A server-side audit helper writes to `operator_events` with `event_type` values prefixed by `peek.`, for example `peek.search`, `peek.user.view_sensitive`, `peek.export`, `peek.access.denied`, `peek.change.applied`, `peek.change.rejected`.\n342:- [ ] Audit payload includes actor email, route, action, resource type, resource id when applicable, query/filter summary, result count when applicable, and request id if available.\n343:- [ ] Mutation audit payload includes before/after values for changed fields, excluding secrets.\n344:- [ ] Rejected mutation attempts log actor email, action id, resource type/id, rejection reason, and no submitted secrets.\n345:- [ ] Audit payload does not include JWTs, access tokens, DB URLs, private keys, raw secrets, or full export contents.\n346:- [ ] Sensitive user detail sections, exports, and all mutations call the audit helper.\n347:- [ ] Audit logging failure does not leak sensitive data to the browser.\n348:- [ ] Audit view reads `operator_events` and filters by event type, actor email, resource id, route, and date.\n349:- [ ] Access to `/audit` can be restricted with the FR-2 page-level allowlist seam.\n356:- [ ] Exports are available only for filtered tables, not for unfiltered full-table dumps.\n357:- [ ] Each export has a server-side row cap.\n358:- [ ] Each export logs a `peek.export` operator event before returning data.\n359:- [ ] Export rows use the same view model fields shown in the table unless explicitly documented.\n360:- [ ] Export filenames include entity, date, and filter slug.\n361:- [ ] Export routes require the same page-level access as the source page.\n362:- [ ] Exports are disabled in production if audit logging is not configured.\n369:- [ ] SQL lives only in `peek/src/server/db/queries/**`.\n370:- [ ] Pages call query functions and receive shaped view models.\n371:- [ ] Browser components receive serializable data only.\n372:- [ ] High-volume tables use pagination, cursoring, or explicit limits.\n373:- [ ] Query functions avoid N+1 patterns for table pages.\n374:- [ ] Heavy pages use required filters, date windows, or manual refresh.\n375:- [ ] Auto-refresh is off by default for heavy pages and never faster than the data can meaningfully change.\n376:- [ ] Query tests cover view-model shaping for null/sparse data.\n377:- [ ] Component tests cover empty, loading, populated, and error states for reusable admin tables/strips.\n384:- [ ] `peek/src/server/mutations/**` is the only place for business-state write actions.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"443dea4c-b718-4ccf-a11b-4dc193e5bf07","uuid":"289d7719-1e92-4f45-b4c7-06e1d7f9a349","timestamp":"2026-04-25T11:13:37.262Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"207:- [ ] Production requests without a valid `cf-access-jwt-assertion` are denied before rendering any page.\n208:- [ ] Production requests with a valid JWT but missing/invalid email claim are denied.\n209:- [ ] JWT validation uses `jose` (`createRemoteJWKSet` + `jwtVerify`) with configured Cloudflare issuer and audience; custom crypto/JWKS verification code is removed.\n210:- [ ] The normalized Cloudflare email is attached to server-side request context and never accepted from an untrusted browser header.\n211:- [ ] `peek` does not maintain a second global env allowlist for base access; base access remains Cloudflare policy.\n212:- [ ] Development bypass is explicit and local-only, for example `PEEK_DEV_ACCESS_EMAIL=dev@example.com`; production never uses this bypass.\n213:- [ ] Unit tests cover missing token, invalid token, missing email, case normalization, trusted context propagation, and development bypass behavior.\n220:- [ ] Access checks are centralized in one server-only module, not repeated in pages.\n221:- [ ] Local role policy is defined in a checked-in server-only module such as `peek/src/server/access-policy.ts`, or in a local config file loaded only by server code.\n222:- [ ] Role membership supports exact emails such as `alice@example.com`.\n223:- [ ] Role membership supports wildcard domains such as `*@example.com`.\n224:- [ ] Role matching is case-insensitive and trims whitespace.\n225:- [ ] Initial roles are limited to `business` and `admin`.\n226:- [ ] A verified email resolves to one effective role; `admin` is the superset role and wins if exact-email and wildcard-domain entries both match.\n227:- [ ] Route prefixes can require `business`, `admin`, or both; sensitive routes such as `/audit` require `admin`.\n228:- [ ] Mutation action ids can require one or more roles, for example `kol_rate.update` requiring `business` or `admin`.\n229:- [ ] Unknown route prefixes use the documented default access behavior; unknown mutation action ids deny.\n230:- [ ] Unit tests cover exact email, wildcard domain, admin precedence, route allow/deny, action allow/deny, case normalization, and invalid policy entries.\n237:- [ ] `peek` has a persistent app shell with navigation groups: Users, Growth, Games, Economy, Operations, Audit, Access.\n238:- [ ] The shell shows the currently verified actor email and resolved local role.\n239:- [ ] The shell never shows pages that the actor cannot access.\n240:- [ ] The first screen remains operationally dense: global search, attention items, a small metric strip, and direct access to the user/referral table.\n241:- [ ] The shell includes no marketing-style hero, decorative analytics filler, or non-actionable dashboard cards.\n242:- [ ] Empty states explain the absence of data in operator terms, for example \"No failed claims in this time window.\"\n249:- [ ] Each metric has a stable id, label, value, source table/query, time window, and \"as of\" timestamp.\n250:- [ ] Each metric has a short definition available in the UI or adjacent help text.\n251:- [ ] Each summary metric links to the filtered detail rows behind it when detail rows exist.\n252:- [ ] Each page states whether data is live, cached, manually refreshed, or sampled.\n253:- [ ] Sparse data renders explicit empty states instead of zeros that can be mistaken for measured outcomes.\n254:- [ ] Monetary values are displayed with units and retain lamports as the precise underlying value.\n255:- [ ] Points and counts use integer formatting; no float rounding for ledger values.\n256:- [ ] Filters are visible and URL-addressable so an admin can share a specific investigation state internally.\n257:- [ ] Default filters prevent accidental unbounded queries on high-volume pages.\n264:- [ ] Search accepts `user_id`, username, wallet, referral code, Telegram username, Telegram provider account id, round PDA, match id, and tx signature.\n265:- [ ] Search results are grouped by entity type: user, referral, linked account, round, transaction, queue event.\n266:- [ ] Each result includes enough context to disambiguate sim